f the church of Hagia Sophia, as well as chariot races, monastic spirituality, diplomacy, and literature. She reveals the fascinating worlds of military usurpers and ascetics, eunuchs and courtesans, and artisans who fashioned the silks, icons, ivories, and mosaics so readily associated with Byzantine art. An innovative history written by one of our foremost scholars, Byzantium reveals this great civilization's rise to military and cultural supremacy, its spectacular destruction by the Fourth Crusade, and its revival and final conquest in 1453.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 7aHISTORY / Ancient / Greece.2bisacsh  aAlexios I Komnenos.  aAnatolia.  aAnna Komnene.  aApse.  aArabs.  aAsia Minor.  aAvars (Caucasus).  aBalkans.  aBasil I.  aBasil II.  aBasilica.  aBelisarius.  aBosphorus.  aByzantine Greeks.  aByzantine art.  aByzantium.  aCaliphate.  aChristendom.  aChristianity.  aCity-state.  aClergy.  aConstantine IX Monomachos.  aConstantine VII.  aConstantine VIII.  aConstantine XI Palaiologos.  aConstantinople.  aCourtier.  aDiocletian.  aDoukas (historian).  aEarly Muslim conquests.  aEastern Mediterranean.  aEcumenical Patriarch of Constantinople.  aEcumenical Patriarchate of Constantinople.  aEcumenical council.  aEunuch.  aFilioque.  aGold coin.  aGreek fire.  aGreeks.  aHeresy.  aHistorian.  aHonorius (emperor).  aIcon.  aIconoclasm.  aImperialism.  aIrene of Athens.  aIslam.  aJews.  aJohn I Tzimiskes.  aJustinian II.  aKomnenos.  aLate Antiquity.  aLatins (Italic tribe).  aLiteracy.  aMacedonian dynasty.  aManuel I Komnenos.  aMichael III.  aMichael VIII Palaiologos.  aMiddle Ages.  aMonastery.  aMosque.  aMount Athos.  aNear East.  aNew Laws.  aNikephoros (Caesar).  aOccupation of 